<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Select Committee, 17October 2013</title></head><body><div><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">vidence from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Suffolk County Council (SRN 033)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council is th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Highway Authority for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and liaises regularly with the Highways Agency, particularly to discuss issues relating to the A14, the main trunk road between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">port</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Felixstowe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and a key route for road hauliers. The county council believes that investment in the A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14 urgently required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and is vital to the future economic prosperity of the county.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">environment?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council welcomes the Department of Transport’s statements that it will be investing £15 billion on adding additional capacity to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s strategic road network by 2021. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It also welcomes the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> intention to spend £12 bil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lion on maintenance and £6 billion on resurfacing. It also welcomes the ambition to bring the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s trunk road network up to clearly defined national standards.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, while the council recognises that these are signif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icant amounts of funding, they s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hould</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not be allocated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the expense of funds like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Local Sustainable Transport Fund and the Cycle Safety Fund. Both of these funds enable local transport authorities to find ways of ensuring that the addition of capacity to the trunk road network will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have minimal negative effects on local communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the form of community severance, noise, light</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and air pollution.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They also help councils encourage use of modes of travel other than the private car which are safe and have significant public health b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as reducing intra-urban traffic congestion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council is using £1.5 million of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Cycle Safety Fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to construct a pedestrian and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycle bridge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> across the A14 to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduce community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">severance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and increase walking and cycling within Bury St. Edmunds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is these funding streams that ensure the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> trunk road network is appropriatel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y pedestrian and cyclist-friendly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and they must not be stopped or reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at the expense of investment that just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ben</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> motorists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council welcomes the additional capital and revenue investment in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s trunk road network. However, the council feels that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this must be embarked upon as part of a coherent inter-urban UK transport strategy for all modes with the aim of using transport as a tool to help facilitate economic growth, but also to ensure the UK meets its environmental obligations and improves the q</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of life for local communities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The council feels that a crucial part of this is to pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ovide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high quality rail services between key urb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an centres and to provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> high quality walk and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> facilities within all urban centres. It also believes the gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnment should increase the volume of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> freight moving on to rail. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These measures will help free up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capacity on the strategic road network for the moto</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rists that have no choice but to use it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Authors of this paper state that, because of improvements in technology and a reduction of insurance costs (in real terms), the cost of motoring will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fall in real terms over the next 30 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Consequently, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">motor traffic, particularly on the strategic network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, will continue to increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strong </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic growth returns. The Council agrees that there are many uncertainties when forecasting traffic growt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h over the longer term (e.g. the way population age composition might mean a change in where different groups of people will live). The government can deal with the many uncertainties by preparing, monitoring and updating a multi-modal transport strategy w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ith focused and relevant objectives, rather than relying on the “predict and provide” approach of past governments.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council also supports the investment of an extra £500 million between 2015 and 2021 in infrastructure to enable greater use of electric vehicles. However, while these vehicles are affective for shorter intra-urban journeys, they might not be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as suitable for longer-distance inter-urban journeys. The Council believes that this could add further uncertainty to the department’s forecasts. Also, technological advancements within the motor car industry should not be used as a reason to reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suppo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rt for longer distance travel by sustainable modes of transport. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council welcomes the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intentions to invest in the different technological solutions mentioned in this document. However, it also feels that the reliability and efficiency of the strategic road network can be improved through The Highways Agency being more proactive than in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">past in its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">engagement with local Highway Authorities and their local stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, Suffolk County Council’s own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highways team has found it difficult in the recent past to share with the Highways Agency its proposals to improve signage at or i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the vicinity of junctions connecting local roads with the A14 in the county.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council feels that greater use of technology and more proactive liaison between The Highways Agency and local Constabularies would enable quicker and more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective responses to accidents and faster clear-up times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which would reduce the length of delays</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk County Council welcomes the aim of increasing investmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t in the strategic network and welcomes the intention to attract investment from sources other than the public sector at a time of public expenditure constraint. It agrees that the move towards 5-year road investment strategies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will give the Highways Agenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y, its suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and contractors the financial certainty to commit to innovative ways of working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that could generate operational efficiency savings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Looking at the exampl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es of other countries and how their governments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have attracted investment in their strategic road networks, the council realises that some form of direct road user charge,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shadow toll,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concession agreement, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or availability payment is part of this. However, it feels that direct road user charging sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould only be implemented as part of a clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, well thought out,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> national trunk road network investment strategy and must apply to all parts of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network so as not to put businesses in one region at a competitive disadvantage to those in another.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must also be a full cost benefit analysis undertaken before any of the above arrangements are introduced.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Council believes that a direct road user charge is the most effective and fair way to manage the demand placed on the s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trategic road network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but it mu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st be implemented throughout the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">universal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pay-as-you-use basis.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> All routes containing a direct road user charge must also have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">untolled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> alternative routes that are suitable for Heavy Goods Vehicles, as many haulage companies have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> policy of not paying road user charges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Should direct road-user charging be introduced across the strategic road network, how will the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure equitable treatment for all road users in terms of charging policy? What mechanisms will be put in place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that prices and price increases are fair and justified when there might be di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fferent financing and contractual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> agreements across the network? For example, arrangements for the M6 toll road might be different to those of the Dartford Crossing, wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ich might affect the price charged to the user over time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is partly for this reason that Suffolk County Council suggests that the performance of the new Strategic Highways Company be monitored by a full economic regulator with a similar remit to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Office for R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ail Regu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lation over Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">network?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Should the Highways Agency be given greater operational independence from government, it needs to be properly regulated and held to account by a full economic regulator. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This would be particularly important should the organisation adopt one o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the operating models mentioned on pages 71-73 of the Action for Roads paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the long term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This organisation must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have the appr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opriate powers to ensure that the company</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consults sufficiently with local authorities and local businesses before embarking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on any investment project. For example, Suffolk County Council feels, along with other stakeholders, that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recent consultation over the A14 Cambridge – Huntingdon investment package </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could have been more effective. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The tone of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Technical Review and O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ptions document</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, published in September 2013</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the very short consultation time, and the lack of engagement with representatives in Suffolk, made it appear that The Highways Agency and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considered the problem and possible solution to be unique to Cambridgeshire and gave scant regard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the vie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ws of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategic road users from outside the county. This is in spite of the considerable financial impact a road user charge would have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on them. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If the Strategic Highways Company were regulated by an organisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">powers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the Office for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Rail Regulation, it would at least have to show that it published market studies and business plans and gave an appropriate time for stakeholders to read and respond to them, either in writing or within a workshop envir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27pt; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Highways Agency (2013), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A14 Cambridge – Huntingdon Improvement Scheme: Technical Review of Options</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, (accessed online), </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243999/a14-technical-review-of-options.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/243999/a14-technical-review-of-options.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>